Project - CreditCard-Customer-Segmentation¶

AllLife Credit Card Customer Segmentation¶

Background¶

AllLife Bank wants to focus on its credit card customer base in the next financial year. They have been advised by their marketing research team, that the penetration in the market can be improved. Based on this input, the Marketing team proposes to run personalised campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers. Another insight from the market research was that the customers perceive the support services of the back poorly. Based on this, the Operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customers queries are resolved faster. Head of Marketing and Head of Delivery both decide to reach out to the Data Science team for help.

Objective¶

To identify different segments in the existing customer based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank.

Key Questions:¶

  1. How many different segments of customers are there?
  2. How are these segments different from each other?
  3. What are your recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers?

Data Description¶

Data is of various customers of a bank with their credit limit, the total number of credit cards the customer has, and different channels through which customer has contacted the bank for any queries, different channels include visiting the bank, online and through a call.

  • Customer key - Identifier for the customer
  • Average Credit Limit - Average credit limit across all the credit cards
  • Total credit cards - Total number of credit cards
  • Total visits bank - Total number of bank visits
  • Total visits online - total number of online visits
  • Total calls made - Total number of calls made by the customer

Steps to follow¶

  1. Perform univariate analysis on the data to better understand the variables at your disposal and to get an idea about the no of clusters. Perform EDA, create visualizations to explore data. (10 marks)
  2. Properly comment on the codes, provide explanations of the steps taken in the notebook and conclude your insights from the graphs. (5 marks)
  3. Execute K-means clustering use elbow plot and analyse clusters using boxplot (10 marks)
  4. Execute hierarchical clustering (with different linkages) with the help of dendrogram and cophenetic coeff. Analyse clusters formed using boxplot (15 marks)
  5. Calculate average silhouette score for both methods. (5 marks)
  6. Compare K-means clusters with Hierarchical clusters. (5 marks)
  7. Analysis the clusters formed, tell us how is one cluster different from another and answer all the key questions. (10 marks)

Create appropriate clusters - K Means Clustering¶

Now, we will use K-Means clustering to group data based on their attribute. First, we need to determine the optimal number of groups. For that we conduct the knee test to see where the knee happens.

In [31]:
# Finding optimal no. of clusters
cluster_range = range(1,10)
cluster_errors = []
for num_clusters in cluster_range:
    clusters = KMeans(num_clusters, n_init = 5,random_state=42)
    clusters.fit(credit_df_scaled)
    labels = clusters.labels_
    centroids = clusters.cluster_centers_
    cluster_errors.append(clusters.inertia_)

clusters_df = pd.DataFrame({"num_clusters": cluster_range, "cluster_errors": cluster_errors})

Elbow Method¶

In [32]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
plt.plot( clusters_df.num_clusters, clusters_df.cluster_errors, marker = "o" )
Out[32]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x7fc78af20350>]

The location of a knee in the plot is usually considered as an indicator of the appropriate number of clusters as it means that adding another cluster does not improve much better the partition.

From the plot above, the optimal point of k where an elbow occurs is at 3.¶

An alternative is to employ the Silhouette Method to find the best k (the optimum number of clusters), which is a better alternative to Elbow Method.

Silhouette Analysis¶

Silhouette analysis can be used to study the separation distance between the resulting clusters. The silhouette plot displays a measure of how close each point in one cluster is to points in the neighboring clusters and thus provides a way to assess parameters like number of clusters visually. This measure has a range of [-1,1]. Average silhouette method computes the average silhouette of observations for different values of k. The optimal number of clusters k is the one that maximize the average silhouette over a range of possible values for k. Lets check the silhouette scores for different numbers of clusters.

In [33]:
from matplotlib import cm
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_samples, silhouette_score

def silh_samp_cluster(clust,  X, start=2, stop=5, metric = 'euclidean'):
    # taken from sebastian Raschkas book Python Machine Learning second edition
    for x in range(start, stop):
        km = clust(n_clusters = x,random_state=42)
        y_km = km.fit_predict(X)
        cluster_labels = np.unique(y_km)
        n_clusters = cluster_labels.shape[0]
        silhouette_vals = silhouette_samples(X, y_km, metric = metric)
        y_ax_lower, y_ax_upper =0,0
        yticks = []
        for i, c in enumerate(cluster_labels):
            c_silhouette_vals = silhouette_vals[y_km == c]
            c_silhouette_vals.sort()
            y_ax_upper += len(c_silhouette_vals)
            color = cm.jet(float(i)/n_clusters)
            plt.barh(range(y_ax_lower, y_ax_upper),
                    c_silhouette_vals,
                    height=1.0,
                    edgecolor='none',
                    color = color)
            yticks.append((y_ax_lower + y_ax_upper)/2.)
            y_ax_lower+= len(c_silhouette_vals)

        silhouette_avg = np.mean(silhouette_vals)
        plt.axvline(silhouette_avg,
                   color = 'red',
                   linestyle = "--")
        plt.yticks(yticks, cluster_labels+1)
        plt.ylabel("Cluster Label")
        plt.xlabel('Silhouette Coefficient')
        plt.title('Silhouette for ' + str(x) + " Clusters")
        plt.show()

Silhouette plots - K Means¶

In [35]:
silh_samp_cluster(KMeans, credit_df_scaled, stop=10)

The red doted line is the mean/average silhouette score for the cluster in consideration.

For a value to be considered as a good value for number of clusters, the following points should be considered:

  • Firstly, The mean value should be as close to 1 as possible
  • Secondly, The plot of each cluster should be above the mean value as much as possible. Any plot region below the mean value is not desirable.
  • Lastly, the width of the plot should be as uniform as possible.

For n_clusters=3, the average silhoutte score is the highest and all the plots are more or less of similar thickness and hence are of similar sizes, and as such can be considered as best ‘k’ value.¶

The plots above shows the distribution of the 3 clusters. We could interpret them as the following customer segments:

  • Cluster 1/Group 0 - Customers with low to moderate average credit limit (with a low to moderate total number of credit cards, but with a moderate number of total visits to the bank. They also seem to have the lowest number of total calls to the bank and lowest number of total online visits)
  • Cluster 2/Group 1 - Customers with the least average credit limit (With least number of total credit cards and least number of total visits to the bank, but with a moderately high number of total calls to the bank
  • Cluster 3/Group 2 - Customers with Highest average credit limit (seem to have high number of credit cards and higher number of total visits online. However they seem to have the lowest total number of bank visits and calls to the bank

Cutting a dendrogram at a certain level gives a set of clusters. To select the "best cut" in dendrograms (i.e., cutting a dendrogram at a particular height) of hierarchical cluster analysis, one of the techniques that can be used is to cut the dendrogram where the difference is most significant. In other words, take the largest difference of heights and count the number of vertical lines seen and that can be the number of clusters. Based on this theory, the optimum number of clusters is 3.

The optimal number of clusters can also be determined by using a mathematical technique such as the silhouette scores.

Silhouette Scores - Agglomerative Clustering¶

In [56]:
from sklearn.cluster import AgglomerativeClustering
In [57]:
silhouette_scores = [] 
for n_cluster in range(2, 10):
    print('Average Silhouette-Score for', n_cluster,  'Clusters: ', silhouette_score(credit_df_scaled, AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters = n_cluster).fit_predict(credit_df_scaled)))
    silhouette_scores.append( 
        silhouette_score(credit_df_scaled, AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters = n_cluster).fit_predict(credit_df_scaled)))

Cophenet index is a measure of the correlation between the distance of points in feature space and distance on dendrogram. The closer it is to 1, the better is the clustering.

  • Group 0/Cluster 1 is characterized by customers with least average credit limit (with lowest number of total credit cards, lowest number of total visits to the bank, but with a high number of total calls to the bank)
  • Group 1/Cluster 2 is characterized by customers with Highest average credit limit (with high number of credit cards and higher number of total visits online.
  • Group 2/Cluster 3 is characterized by customers with low to moderate average credit limit and total number of credit cards, but with a moderate number of total visits to the bank. They also seem to have lower number of total number of calls to the bank.

Summary¶

Both the clustering techniques used above (K-Means and Agglomerative Hierarchial clustering) seem to segment the customers into essentially the same number of clusters and based on similar criteria. The customers are segmented based on their average credit limit across all their credit cards.

The customers with the least average credit limit (consequently the lowest total number of credit cards) seem to prefer calling the bank rather than in person visits and online high number of total calls to the bank.

The customers with Highest average credit limit and high number of credit cards, seem to higher number of total visits online. This group also seems to have lower number of total calls and lower number of total visits to bank indicating that their preferred channel of communication is online.

Better online marketing and service/support strategies targeting this group of customers should be considered.

There are also customers with moderate average credit limit and total number of credit cards, and their preferred mode of communication seem to be in person bank visits. To expand their customer base and attract these customers, the bank needs to incorporate better in person service/support strategies as well.
